__NOTOC__ __NOEDITSECTION__

Prepayments, also called deferrals, result from cash payment proceeds an expense or revenue recognition.  The most common example of a prepaid expense is unearned revenue.

Often, businesses pay for services from which they have not yet benefited e.g. rent is often paid in advance.

The double entry for a prepayment is:

{{bookkeeping journal
| page = 1
| entry =
{{bookkeeping entry| date = 2005<br/>Feb | day = 1 | description = Prepaid Rent (Asset) | dr = 50 }}
{{bookkeeping entry| description = Cash (Asset) | cr = 50 }}
}}


Later when the rent is actually due the entry is:

{{bookkeeping journal
| page = 1
| entry =
{{bookkeeping entry| date = 2005<br/>Mar | day = 1 | description = Rent (Expense) | dr = 50 }}
{{bookkeeping entry| description = Prepaid Rent (Asset) | cr = 50 }}
}}

{{BookCat}}

{{Bookeeping Journal Start| name = | page = 1 }}
{{Bookeeping Journal Dr| date = {{{date}}} | day = {{{day}}} | description = {{{dr}}} | post= | dr = {{{amount}}} }}
{{Bookeeping Journal Cr| description = {{{cr}}} | post= | cr = {{{amount}}} }}
{{Bookeeping Journal Finish}}<noinclude>[[Category:Accountancy/Templates|{{PAGENAME}}]]</noinclude>

