{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Impedimenta| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]] (Jinx)| features=Causes the target to trip| appearance=}}
== Overview ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
'''''Impedimenta ''''' is a jinx that causes the victim to trip, get blasted backwards, etc. The power of the jinx is affected by how much you concentrate when saying the incantation.
== Analysis ==
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Finite Incantatem| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]] (Charm)| features=Stops running spells| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Chamber of Secrets/Chapter 11|''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'']]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Finite Incantatem''''' is a spell that causes easier ongoing spells and jinxes to stop.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
Many charms, hexes, and jinxes have ongoing effects; [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Rictusempra|Rictusempra]], for instance, causes endless tickling, while [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Tarantallegra|Tarantallegra]] causes endless "dancing" (uncontrollable leg movement). The Finite Incantatem spell can be used to stop all these ongoing effects.
== Analysis ==
Presumably, the wizard casting Finite Incantatem must be more powerful, possibly significantly more powerful, than the wizard casting the original spell, or Finite Incantatem would be taught as a defensive spell and would be much more widely used in dueling. As it is, we only see this spell used twice: in the Dueling Club, [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Snape]] uses it to stop all of the jinxes that have been fired by the students, and after the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Major Events/Battle at the Department of Mysteries|Battle in the Ministry]], [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Remus Lupin|Lupin]] uses it to stop the Tarantallegra curse that is affecting [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Neville Longbottom|Neville]].
Some jinxes have more of a one-shot effect; [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Stupefy|Stupefy]], for instance, which renders someone unconscious. Finite Incantatem would have no effect on jinxes of that nature.
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
